00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:29.320
HUGH MCMANUS: Welcome to
the Variability Simulation.

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:32.170
This should look
kind of familiar.

00:00:32.170 --> 00:00:35.330
This is a much simpler
simulation than before.

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:37.960
It's not going to
take all day, but it's

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:41.650
going to illustrate one
point very well, which

00:00:41.650 --> 00:00:44.500
is what's the impact
of variability

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:45.970
on process performance?

00:00:45.970 --> 00:00:48.070
That's our learning
objective and we're

00:00:48.070 --> 00:00:52.430
going to look at it through
the poker chip simulation.

00:00:52.430 --> 00:00:54.487
We're going to look at
a computer simulation

00:00:54.487 --> 00:00:56.320
because one of the
problems with variability

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:58.570
is sometimes to understand
a variable system,

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:02.110
you need a lot of
data, a lot of cases.

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:08.500
And we're also going to explore
some simple relationships that

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:14.290
help us, including that
cue-theory equation that Earll

00:01:14.290 --> 00:01:18.070
showed, to help us understand
variable processes.

00:01:18.070 --> 00:01:23.170
This is a piece of a rather
old data on an engineering

00:01:23.170 --> 00:01:25.060
process with high variability.

00:01:25.060 --> 00:01:27.970
The traditional
process shown here

00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:30.910
a the high cycle time
and high variability

00:01:30.910 --> 00:01:33.820
was actually the process
that was value stream mapped

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:36.850
in the module we
showed, I believe

00:01:36.850 --> 00:01:40.840
it was two rays ago, that had
that very messy value stream

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:43.400
map with all the arrows
going everywhere.

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:45.370
It was a very
unpredictable process.

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:47.680
It ended up having
very high variability.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:49.720
Now, the problem
with that, given

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.390
that that process was embedded
in a larger process, which

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:55.300
was to produce an airplane, it
was just the drawing release

00:01:55.300 --> 00:01:56.110
process.

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:58.270
The problem wasn't
even so much the fact

00:01:58.270 --> 00:02:01.340
that it took a long time,
although that wasn't great.

00:02:01.340 --> 00:02:04.720
The problem was that the
variability was almost as high

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:08.289
as the actual time, which means
it could take almost no time,

00:02:08.289 --> 00:02:10.180
it could take double
the amount of time.

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:14.170
And how easy is it
to do organized work

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:19.210
in an environment where even the
allegedly simple processes are

00:02:19.210 --> 00:02:21.220
so unpredictable?

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:22.298
It's very bad.

00:02:22.298 --> 00:02:24.340
Now, they managed to
actually do a lot about that

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:28.090
by applying Lean,
but you can see

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:32.130
how disruptive that high
variability is going to be.

00:02:32.130 --> 00:02:34.750
The accounts payable module
also reinforced that,

00:02:34.750 --> 00:02:36.850
that the high
variability was very

00:02:36.850 --> 00:02:38.560
destructive to that process.

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:41.050
On top of that, you're going
to have quality problems

00:02:41.050 --> 00:02:42.580
with a variable process.

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:43.750
That's highly likely.

00:02:43.750 --> 00:02:46.300
They may be variable
because of mistakes,

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:49.330
or it may be that the variable
process makes it easier

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:51.340
to make mistakes.

00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:53.290
And then we're
also going to talk,

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:57.490
both in Six Sigma and today,
about the process capability

00:02:57.490 --> 00:02:59.890
being affected by variability.

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:03.510
So we're going to do, I said
this already, a dice game.

00:03:03.510 --> 00:03:05.260
We're going to do a
computer sim and we're

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:07.480
going to look at some
simple relationships.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:09.893
We're also going to
sort of foreshadow

00:03:09.893 --> 00:03:12.310
some stuff we're going to do
in the Quality and Six Sigma.

00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:14.040
Not on these bullets--

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:15.730
I'm talking fast
right now because I'm

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:18.550
going to try to carve
out a little bit of time

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:21.700
at the end to discuss
some of the things

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:24.340
you can do about
variability because I

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:26.590
think that's particularly
important to our health care

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:27.173
audience.

00:03:27.173 --> 00:03:29.590
To some extent, our engineers,
but particularly our health

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:30.730
care people.

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:33.460
One of the big
issues with applying

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:37.450
any kind of process improvement
in a very high variability

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:39.400
environment is just
getting your mind

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.350
wrapped around what does
an average mean, what

00:03:41.350 --> 00:03:46.450
does even a standard
deviation mean in a process

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:48.910
where the variability
has weird distributions

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:51.820
and odd special
cases and outliers?

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:53.860
We'll try to carve out
a little bit of time

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:56.140
to actually talk about some
of the practical things

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:59.050
you can do to get
variability under control.

00:03:59.050 --> 00:04:00.910
Here's a perfect system.

00:04:00.910 --> 00:04:02.860
What you are sitting
in front of is

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:06.850
a perfect, balanced,
single-piece flow

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:08.800
system, or near single.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.330
It's a very small-batch system.

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:14.710
It has tasks arranged
in order in, actually,

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:17.390
a U-shaped shaped cell.

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:19.510
It's not a pull cell,
it's more of a push cell,

00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:22.510
but still, it's a U-shaped cell.

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:26.140
Every task has an inventory in
front of it, a little buffer

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.870
inventory to make sure
that it has the things it

00:04:28.870 --> 00:04:30.790
needs to do to do its work.

00:04:30.790 --> 00:04:33.230
Every task is
perfectly balanced,

00:04:33.230 --> 00:04:38.230
so there's no bottlenecks
in the system.

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:42.700
The only thing imperfect about
the system is its variability.

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:45.910
And this half of
the room, your mats

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:52.165
actually say mailroom
and PFR check and, well,

00:04:52.165 --> 00:04:53.560
you get the picture.

00:04:53.560 --> 00:04:57.460
We're looking at the accounts
payable process here.

00:04:57.460 --> 00:04:59.500
You guys on the health
care side actually

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:02.560
have familiar-looking
mats from yesterday

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:04.300
because you had a
process that had

00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:07.750
variability issues yesterday.

00:05:07.750 --> 00:05:10.930
The point here, both sides
of the room are identical.

00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:13.150
And the point we're
actually trying to make here

00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:15.820
is an awful lot of
processes look like this.

00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:19.070
Even if you get them perfect, if
they have variability in them,

00:05:19.070 --> 00:05:22.360
they're going to behave in
ways that are actually even

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:24.890
worse than one might expect.

00:05:24.890 --> 00:05:28.300
So let's find out how
this system behaves.

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:29.530
This is the game.

00:05:29.530 --> 00:05:32.890
It's a very simple game.

00:05:32.890 --> 00:05:38.590
What we're going to ask
you to do is every day--

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:41.590
we're going to call
the shifts day--

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:43.600
we are going to process chips.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:48.190
We are going to process one
six-sided die worth of chips,

00:05:48.190 --> 00:05:50.590
so anywhere from
one to six chips.

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:52.270
There's our variability.

00:05:52.270 --> 00:05:54.940
The way we are going
to process them is we

00:05:54.940 --> 00:05:57.770
are going to pick up
chips from our inbox.

00:05:57.770 --> 00:06:00.280
If you are the customer
or patient person,

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:02.020
you have a big pile
of chips, so you have

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:03.670
an infinite quantity of chips.

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:05.060
Just pick up chips from there.

00:06:05.060 --> 00:06:06.880
Everybody else has
a finite number

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:09.730
of chips that they can pick
up, the ones in their inbox.

00:06:09.730 --> 00:06:14.980
So you will be rolling a dice,
picking up that number of chips

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:15.760
from your inbox.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:18.225
If you don't have
enough, OK, too bad.

00:06:18.225 --> 00:06:19.600
If you roll a 6
and you only have

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:21.850
three, which is what
everybody has now,

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:24.400
then you just pick up the three.

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:28.330
And then everybody at the
same time, to avoid confusion,

00:06:28.330 --> 00:06:31.510
passes those chips,
the number of chips

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:36.310
that they can pass, to
the next person in line.

00:06:36.310 --> 00:06:38.020
And then at the
end of each day, we

00:06:38.020 --> 00:06:40.870
will write down how
many chips we passed.

00:06:40.870 --> 00:06:46.450
The only tricky part about that
is that both the archive here

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:49.030
and the discharge
there, a certain number

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:51.610
of chips every day
will go into that mat,

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:55.570
and the customers
or the patients

00:06:55.570 --> 00:06:57.310
have to record that number.

00:06:57.310 --> 00:07:00.340
That's kind of the overall
throughput of the system.

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:02.680
So that's a slight
trickiness at the end.

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:04.540
That's what we're going to do.

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:07.900
So for example, here's day one.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:09.550
Everybody has three chips.

00:07:09.550 --> 00:07:12.430
If this person rolls a 3,
they pick up all three chips,

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:13.960
send them along.

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:16.840
This person rolls a 2, they
can only pick up two chips.

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:19.990
This person rolls a 5, they
can only pick up three chips

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:21.610
because that's all they have.

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:24.530
No waiting for this person
to send the two along,

00:07:24.530 --> 00:07:25.577
so then you have five--

00:07:25.577 --> 00:07:26.410
no, that's cheating.

00:07:30.190 --> 00:07:34.340
The chips only get passed
one station per day.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.460
This person rolls
a 1, et cetera.

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:39.430
This person rolls a 6, they only
had three, so they pass three.

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:42.430
And then this is what it looks
like at the end of that day.

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:44.660
Three have been
passed along, two out,

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:46.390
so the inventory went up.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:50.140
Three came out, two went in,
so that went down a little bit.

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:54.310
Three went in, only one
left, so that's got more.

00:07:54.310 --> 00:07:57.440
Let's see, one went
in and three came out,

00:07:57.440 --> 00:07:59.080
so that person only has one.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:02.630
The overall throughput
of the system was three.

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:06.970
We're going to record how many
did you do, how many did you

00:08:06.970 --> 00:08:07.820
pass along?

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:10.510
So either your die roll
or how many you had,

00:08:10.510 --> 00:08:11.980
whatever number is smaller.

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:13.480
How many did you pass along?

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:15.220
And then at the
end of the round,

00:08:15.220 --> 00:08:16.510
what is your work in progress?

00:08:16.510 --> 00:08:19.300
So everyone starts with three,
so that number is already

00:08:19.300 --> 00:08:20.170
filled in.

00:08:20.170 --> 00:08:23.240
At the end of each day, you're
going to record your number.

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:25.070
Yeah, so here's an example.

00:08:25.070 --> 00:08:29.420
Our person there passed one job
along and some work built up,

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:35.770
so at the end of that day,
they had five, et cetera.

00:08:35.770 --> 00:08:37.780
The customer or
patient worksheet

00:08:37.780 --> 00:08:40.150
is a little bit more
complicated because they're

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:42.870
sending the work out.

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:45.370
That's basically always going
to be the die roll because you

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:48.930
have lots and lots of chips.

00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:51.930
You're going to record the
number of jobs that actually

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:54.660
came through the system,
and here, the U-shaped cell

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:55.930
is going to help us.

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:57.630
So the number of
jobs that are added--

00:08:57.630 --> 00:09:02.450
not in, but added-- to the
finished pile at each round

00:09:02.450 --> 00:09:04.763
is recorded here.

00:09:04.763 --> 00:09:06.180
And then you're
also going to keep

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:08.880
track of the total WIP on the
whole table, the total work

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:11.460
in progress in the whole
table, which starts at 12.

00:09:11.460 --> 00:09:13.240
Now, you could just
count every time,

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:16.050
but that would be really
slow, so instead, we're

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:18.630
going to use a conservation law.

00:09:18.630 --> 00:09:21.870
Earll's an old aerodynamicist,
so they love conservation laws,

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:24.480
right?

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:28.560
A former, a retired
aerodynamicist.

00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:29.970
A former aerodynamicist.

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:31.200
They love conservation laws.

00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:33.180
This is the conservation
of chips laws.

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:37.290
If you know that you sent out
six and three got finished,

00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:39.540
then three must have
gone into the system.

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:42.510
And they didn't fall on the
floor or get eaten or anything,

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:45.083
so this number must
have gone up by three.

00:09:45.083 --> 00:09:46.500
So there's a little
equation there

00:09:46.500 --> 00:09:53.040
that will help you figure
out the new work in progress.

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:56.037
So everybody think they
can do that much math?

00:09:56.037 --> 00:09:58.120
And I think that's actually
written on your sheet,

00:09:58.120 --> 00:10:01.360
so you should be
able to do that.

00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:02.890
OK, and there's an example.

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:06.040
If three go in and three
come out, it stays the same.

00:10:06.040 --> 00:10:10.540
If two go in and one comes
out, then that extra chip

00:10:10.540 --> 00:10:13.450
must be sitting on the
table, so it goes up by one.

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:16.510
And we can keep doing
that ad infinitum.

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:18.267
OK, what do we
think should happen?

00:10:18.267 --> 00:10:20.850
AUDIENCE: Maybe we should just
ask if there are any questions.

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:23.030
HUGH MCMANUS: Any questions
about the process?

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:26.950
AUDIENCE: So I [INAUDIBLE]
and I roll the die,

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:30.040
and I get like, 5.

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:32.610
So I pass on three because
I only have three chips.

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:35.110
HUGH MCMANUS: Because you only
have the three, that's right.

00:10:35.110 --> 00:10:38.160
AUDIENCE: So under
patients completed,

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:39.130
I'll have three there?

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:40.547
HUGH MCMANUS: You
put three, yeah.

00:10:40.547 --> 00:10:43.143
AUDIENCE: Then what will
now be the work in progress?

00:10:43.143 --> 00:10:44.560
HUGH MCMANUS: The
work in progress

00:10:44.560 --> 00:10:48.340
is whatever the person
next to you gives to you.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:51.340
Because everybody's going to
pass them at the same time.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:53.048
We're going to be very
formal about that.

00:10:53.048 --> 00:10:54.882
We're going to have a
standard process where

00:10:54.882 --> 00:10:57.770
we're going to ask everybody to
pass them all at the same time.

00:10:57.770 --> 00:10:59.770
So then yeah, you'll just
have to look and see--

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:00.820
AUDIENCE: It's
actually what you have

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:02.155
left by the end of the round.

00:11:02.155 --> 00:11:03.280
HUGH MCMANUS: That's right.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:04.330
That's correct.

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:07.420
AUDIENCE: If you rolled a
3 and had four chips here,

00:11:07.420 --> 00:11:10.730
you would move three, and you'd
take one left plus whatever

00:11:10.730 --> 00:11:11.230
new stuff--

00:11:11.230 --> 00:11:12.490
HUGH MCMANUS: Plus
whatever payment.

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:14.080
So it's whatever's
sitting on that mat

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:17.590
at the end of the round
is your work in progress.

00:11:17.590 --> 00:11:22.360
So the average of a
six-sided die is 3 and 1/2,

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:26.210
so what do we think this system
should be able to do over--

00:11:26.210 --> 00:11:27.790
we're going to do 20 rounds.

00:11:27.790 --> 00:11:30.123
What do we think it should
be able to do over 20 rounds?

00:11:32.210 --> 00:11:33.640
Is it going to
process 3 and 1/2?

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:35.240
Are these die rolls
going to even out?

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:40.010
Maybe.

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:42.688
Everyone's thinking.

00:11:42.688 --> 00:11:44.560
AUDIENCE: 60?

00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:46.880
HUGH MCMANUS: 60, so
that would be 3ish.

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:49.070
So it's not going to
be perfect, but it's

00:11:49.070 --> 00:11:50.670
going to be close to evened out.

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:52.420
AUDIENCE: So we don't
process more than 3.

00:11:52.420 --> 00:11:54.355
[INAUDIBLE]

00:11:54.355 --> 00:11:55.980
HUGH MCMANUS: Yeah,
in the first round,

00:11:55.980 --> 00:11:57.680
you're only going to get 3.

00:11:57.680 --> 00:11:59.840
More will come in
as the customer

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:02.360
person rolls their dice.

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:04.664
The initiating person.

00:12:04.664 --> 00:12:07.075
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:12:07.075 --> 00:12:07.818
You think less?

00:12:07.818 --> 00:12:08.318
Less, OK.

00:12:08.318 --> 00:12:18.300
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:12:18.300 --> 00:12:18.800
