Boink, I just ran it again.

00:24:54.290 --> 00:24:56.010
Came out different.

00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:59.020
If I run it again, different.

00:24:59.020 --> 00:25:02.550
Even the gross behavior of
the system is not predictable.

00:25:02.550 --> 00:25:06.430
It doesn't like, get bigger
and then kind of even off.

00:25:06.430 --> 00:25:08.770
If I ran it a billion
times and took the average,

00:25:08.770 --> 00:25:11.145
I'd actually get sort
of a logarithmic curve

00:25:11.145 --> 00:25:12.520
where it would go
up and steadily

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:15.550
flatten out, although never
actually reach an equilibrium.

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:18.760
But the behavior even
over a large number

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:20.800
of rounds of any given
instance of this system

00:25:20.800 --> 00:25:22.540
is extremely unpredictable.

00:25:22.540 --> 00:25:25.510
So perfect system
except for variability.

00:25:25.510 --> 00:25:30.090
The variability is making
the system behave very badly.

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:31.530
OK, what can we do about this?

00:25:31.530 --> 00:25:33.530
The other nice thing about
a computer simulation

00:25:33.530 --> 00:25:36.000
is we can change
it relatively easy.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:40.300
We could, for example, lower
the customer input variability.

00:25:40.300 --> 00:25:42.630
That's a favorite
of bad processes.

00:25:42.630 --> 00:25:44.427
People say, it's our
customer's fault.

00:25:44.427 --> 00:25:46.260
There's too much customer
input variability.

00:25:46.260 --> 00:25:50.850
Like all patients show up Friday
night, so it's not our fault.

00:25:50.850 --> 00:25:53.580
Let's lower the customer
input variability some.

00:25:56.143 --> 00:25:57.060
Didn't help very much.

00:25:57.060 --> 00:25:58.680
Let's lower it a lot.

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:00.180
Didn't help very much.

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:01.290
Why?

00:26:01.290 --> 00:26:03.880
That appeared to
help a little bit.

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:05.310
Yeah, that's a little better.

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:09.420
That's with a lot less
customer input variability.

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:12.210
But basically, both count.

00:26:12.210 --> 00:26:14.640
The process variability
and the customer input

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:17.270
variability count a lot.

00:26:17.270 --> 00:26:19.160
Let's do this, though.

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:24.260
Let's lower the customer
demand just a little bit.

00:26:24.260 --> 00:26:29.770
Oh, it looks about the same as
lowering the variability a lot.

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:33.300
Let's lower the
customer demand 20%.

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:41.415
Doesn't look great,
but what's changed?

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:51.060
It looks like there's a lot
less variability in the process.

00:26:53.700 --> 00:27:00.090
And if we lower the
customer variability by 30%,

00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:03.750
there's still variability,
but the system can handle it.

00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:05.970
Essentially we're
destressing the system,

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:10.200
running it at a little bit
less than 100% capacity,

00:27:10.200 --> 00:27:12.340
and it behaves a lot better.

00:27:12.340 --> 00:27:14.550
And this was brought
up in the AP system

00:27:14.550 --> 00:27:17.740
where they were running
at 100% capacity.

00:27:17.740 --> 00:27:19.020
It's the same in this system.

00:27:19.020 --> 00:27:23.850
Basically, if we try to stress
it, we only get about 70%.

00:27:23.850 --> 00:27:26.970
If we say, you know, it's only
going to run at 70% anyway,

00:27:26.970 --> 00:27:29.010
let's just give it
70% of the load.

00:27:29.010 --> 00:27:31.380
It actually behaves pretty well.

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:36.540
This is a nonintuitive
effect unless you're

00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:37.540
one of those workers.

00:27:37.540 --> 00:27:40.140
What happens if you have
to work all the time

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:41.220
and something goes wrong?

00:27:41.220 --> 00:27:42.180
Chaos, right?

00:27:42.180 --> 00:27:43.980
Crap, I have to
stay up all night,

00:27:43.980 --> 00:27:48.040
but I can't, I'm too tired,
so things just go to hell.

00:27:48.040 --> 00:27:51.240
What happens if you
have six hours of work

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:53.220
in an eight-hour day and
something goes wrong?

00:27:55.970 --> 00:27:58.900
You can fix it.

00:27:58.900 --> 00:28:00.820
From an individual
worker's point of view,

00:28:00.820 --> 00:28:03.310
this is very easy to understand.

00:28:03.310 --> 00:28:05.383
The system effect seems
kind of mysterious,

00:28:05.383 --> 00:28:08.050
but actually, if you think about
what's happening on the ground,

00:28:08.050 --> 00:28:09.970
if the system is
not fully stressed,

00:28:09.970 --> 00:28:11.740
it can handle variability.

00:28:11.740 --> 00:28:15.010
And you don't have to back off
on the system all that much

00:28:15.010 --> 00:28:19.170
to handle quite a
lot of variability.

00:28:19.170 --> 00:28:21.420
Yeah, I understand that
we're tight on time.

00:28:21.420 --> 00:28:26.890
We're coming to a
close here fortunately.

00:28:26.890 --> 00:28:28.900
So that's kind of magic.

00:28:28.900 --> 00:28:31.720
The other thing we can
do is attack variability,

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:34.810
and if we attack
variability heroically--

00:28:34.810 --> 00:28:40.210
let's reduce variability
30% across the board--

00:28:40.210 --> 00:28:41.680
it helps some.

00:28:44.530 --> 00:28:48.760
Yeah, it's better, but it's
still behaving kind of badly.

00:28:48.760 --> 00:28:52.030
If we reduce variability
70% across the board,

00:28:52.030 --> 00:28:55.037
this is truly heroic
variability reduction.

00:29:00.030 --> 00:29:02.550
That didn't work well.

00:29:02.550 --> 00:29:05.050
Oh, there we go.

00:29:05.050 --> 00:29:08.070
Notice when it was all but
one, it was still no good.

00:29:08.070 --> 00:29:10.920
We have now reduced variability
heroically across the board,

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:14.520
we've got about the same level
of effect as reducing the--

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:19.680
so apparently, according to
the simulation, what we need

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:26.850
is either heroic variability
reduction or a modest decrease

00:29:26.850 --> 00:29:29.230
in the load on the system.

00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:33.900
And this is actually a very
powerful practical lesson

00:29:33.900 --> 00:29:37.170
and it comes from
that same equation

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:40.180
that Earll was showing.

00:29:40.180 --> 00:29:44.110
If we're mathematically
inclined here,

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:45.490
what happens when
our utilization

00:29:45.490 --> 00:29:48.680
is very high on this term?

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:51.870
Just put a 1 in there and see
what happens mathematically.

00:29:51.870 --> 00:29:53.750
It goes to infinity, right?

00:29:53.750 --> 00:29:55.320
If the system is
completely loaded

00:29:55.320 --> 00:29:57.630
and there's any
variability at all,

00:29:57.630 --> 00:30:01.430
it will just continue to get
worse and worse in its behavior

00:30:01.430 --> 00:30:04.130
if it's 100% loaded.

00:30:04.130 --> 00:30:06.960
The variability was
actually squared,

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:10.410
so if we can reduce
variability, that's good,

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:13.080
but this effect is actually
even more powerful.

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:17.880
And if we plot the
two effects, here's

00:30:17.880 --> 00:30:22.020
a plot of what happens
if we control variability

00:30:22.020 --> 00:30:23.370
for various utilizations.

00:30:23.370 --> 00:30:27.330
If we have a heavily loaded
system-- that's this one--

00:30:27.330 --> 00:30:29.670
and we reduce
variability, once we've

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:31.710
driven it down really low--

00:30:31.710 --> 00:30:33.513
this is the cue
time or inventory,

00:30:33.513 --> 00:30:34.680
they're basically the same--

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:40.710
it will start to behave.

00:30:40.710 --> 00:30:43.260
But if there's
noticeable variation

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:47.040
on a heavily loaded system,
it's going to behave badly.

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:50.585
If it's not so heavily loaded,
it almost doesn't matter.

00:30:50.585 --> 00:30:52.710
This is a lightly loaded
system and the variability

00:30:52.710 --> 00:30:54.793
doesn't matter, this is a
moderately loaded system

00:30:54.793 --> 00:30:57.510
and reducing
variability is good.

00:30:57.510 --> 00:31:00.090
And that's not really
linear, but basically,

00:31:00.090 --> 00:31:02.610
sort of proportionally,
if we reduce variability,

00:31:02.610 --> 00:31:03.960
we get better behavior.

00:31:03.960 --> 00:31:05.610
But in a very heavily
loaded system,

00:31:05.610 --> 00:31:07.350
we really have to drive it to 0.

00:31:07.350 --> 00:31:09.430
This is Six Sigma.

00:31:09.430 --> 00:31:12.070
If we have a system that we
want to load really heavily,

00:31:12.070 --> 00:31:15.550
we want to make
billions of ICs, then

00:31:15.550 --> 00:31:18.010
we have to drive the
variability very close to 0

00:31:18.010 --> 00:31:20.570
to get the system to behave.

00:31:20.570 --> 00:31:22.690
This is the converse thought.

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:25.900
If we ease off on utilization
for various variabilities,

00:31:25.900 --> 00:31:27.490
what we see is that
blow-up effect,

00:31:27.490 --> 00:31:30.730
that divided by 0 as
we get close to 1.

00:31:30.730 --> 00:31:33.160
And it's almost independent
of the variability level.

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:39.190
At any level, if we back off
some from 100% utilization,

00:31:39.190 --> 00:31:41.890
the behavior actually
gets a lot better.

00:31:41.890 --> 00:31:42.980
Question?

00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:47.050
AUDIENCE: I'm just wondering how
organizational management deals

00:31:47.050 --> 00:31:49.510
with this fact if
they know that they

00:31:49.510 --> 00:31:51.728
need to operate significantly
under their capacity--

00:31:51.728 --> 00:31:53.395
HUGH MCMANUS: That's
a tough one, right?

00:31:53.395 --> 00:31:55.228
AUDIENCE: --in order
to control their system

00:31:55.228 --> 00:31:59.275
versus having a perfect
system without variation.

00:31:59.275 --> 00:32:00.400
HUGH MCMANUS: That's right.

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:00.942
That's right.

00:32:00.942 --> 00:32:03.760
Managers like Six Sigma because
if your system is perfect,

00:32:03.760 --> 00:32:06.220
you can load it at 100%.

00:32:06.220 --> 00:32:07.450
They want to hear that.

00:32:07.450 --> 00:32:09.490
That's a message
they want to hear.

00:32:09.490 --> 00:32:11.980
In systems like health
care or engineering,

00:32:11.980 --> 00:32:16.840
getting the variability very,
very low is very, very hard.

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:21.580
And this is a very rich field.

00:32:21.580 --> 00:32:23.470
In the interest
of time, I'm going

00:32:23.470 --> 00:32:28.010
to jump to a couple
of useful tips.

00:32:28.010 --> 00:32:32.205
One is that one of
the purposes of Lean,

00:32:32.205 --> 00:32:33.580
and this was
actually illustrated

00:32:33.580 --> 00:32:35.650
very nicely by
the AP case study,

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:38.140
is to free up those resources.

00:32:38.140 --> 00:32:42.800
Not in order to lay people off
or necessarily save money even,

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:48.910
but if you can take 10% or 20%
of your non-value-added time

00:32:48.910 --> 00:32:51.640
out of your day, what
does that get you?

00:32:51.640 --> 00:32:54.190
That gets you that
headroom that allows

00:32:54.190 --> 00:32:56.800
you to deal with variability.

00:32:56.800 --> 00:33:00.640
And it's one of the sort of
root causes of why Lean seems

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:04.330
to have a magic effect
of increasing quality

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:07.720
and throughput time when that's
not even what you're aiming at.

00:33:07.720 --> 00:33:09.370
If you just take
waste out of a system,

00:33:09.370 --> 00:33:12.130
suddenly everybody in the system
has a little bit of extra time

00:33:12.130 --> 00:33:17.050
to deal with variation, to
deal with things going wrong.

00:33:17.050 --> 00:33:21.860
So that's sort of
the hint, number one.

00:33:21.860 --> 00:33:26.260
The other thing is that in
terms of variability reduction,

00:33:26.260 --> 00:33:28.670
although that's an art,
there's no one answer.

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:34.200
There are things
that help a lot.

00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:36.870
Reducing something like
health care variability to 0

00:33:36.870 --> 00:33:41.370
is obviously not even
possible, but one

00:33:41.370 --> 00:33:44.400
of the things about
actually both health

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:46.170
care and engineering-type
processes

00:33:46.170 --> 00:33:48.960
is that the distributions
aren't really normal.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:51.160
It tends to be like, a
bunch of standard cases

00:33:51.160 --> 00:33:54.150
and then some wacko ones.

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:56.162
Well, what happens
to the variability

00:33:56.162 --> 00:33:58.620
in terms of those equations if
you just take the wacko ones

00:33:58.620 --> 00:33:59.300
off the table?

00:34:02.490 --> 00:34:03.960
Gets a lot better, right?

00:34:03.960 --> 00:34:05.260
It gets a lot better.

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:10.080
So essentially, special case
handling for the outliers.

00:34:10.080 --> 00:34:12.162
In the simulation
game, we originally

00:34:12.162 --> 00:34:13.620
designed the health
care simulation

00:34:13.620 --> 00:34:15.495
to be part of a three-day
seminar where you'd

00:34:15.495 --> 00:34:19.110
play that last round at the
end, like after this lesson,

00:34:19.110 --> 00:34:21.500
and there's something in there
called a patient advocate.

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:23.830
Anybody even look at that card?

00:34:23.830 --> 00:34:25.680
What did it do?

00:34:25.680 --> 00:34:28.679
AUDIENCE: It helped
those patients that

00:34:28.679 --> 00:34:31.025
would take the most
amount of time and helped

00:34:31.025 --> 00:34:32.400
shepherd them
through the system.

00:34:32.400 --> 00:34:34.199
HUGH MCMANUS: Right, exactly.

00:34:34.199 --> 00:34:37.739
In terms of the simulation,
it took the 6's off, right?

00:34:37.739 --> 00:34:40.350
And if you looked at
the distributions,

00:34:40.350 --> 00:34:41.639
they were highly non-standard.

00:34:41.639 --> 00:34:43.199
The 6's were horrible.

00:34:43.199 --> 00:34:48.090
And so that's actually
a real example

00:34:48.090 --> 00:34:52.500
of taking the really difficult
cases out of the standard flow

00:34:52.500 --> 00:34:54.929
of the system, and that
makes the standard flow

00:34:54.929 --> 00:34:55.679
work a lot better.

00:34:55.679 --> 00:34:57.554
Of course, you have to
devote some resources,

00:34:57.554 --> 00:35:00.000
some special resources,
to the difficult people.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:03.420
But there's ways you can
kind of knock the top off

00:35:03.420 --> 00:35:06.660
of high variabilities that
can help a lot on that side.

00:35:06.660 --> 00:35:09.090
On the capacity
side, the real key

00:35:09.090 --> 00:35:13.020
is to use the benefits
of any kind of Lean

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:15.210
to essentially plow
them back into making

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:20.070
people's lives easier so they
have a little bit of extra time

00:35:20.070 --> 00:35:22.880
to absorb the variability.